# helgrind.supp -- two suppressions for a helgrind/glibc disagreement, not
# for anything in your code.
#
# glibc 2.34 and later implement pthread_cond_wait with an internal reference
# count that it manipulates with futex operations while the caller's mutex is
# not held. helgrind models the older implementation, sees those operations,
# and reports
#
#     pthread_cond_{signal,broadcast}: associated lock is not held by calling
#     thread
#
# with a stack whose top frames are inside glibc's __pthread_cond_wait_common
# -- that is, inside pthread_cond_wait, on the way IN, before any of your code
# has done anything. A correct semaphore produces several of these per
# run and there is nothing to fix.
#
# Both suppressions require __pthread_cond_wait_common to be on the stack, so
# they are narrow. The mistake they could plausibly hide -- calling
# pthread_cond_signal without holding the mutex -- produces the same message
# from a completely different stack, with pthread_cond_signal and your
# msem_post or msem_wait on it and no __pthread_cond_wait_common
# anywhere, and is still reported.
# That was checked by building a version that signals outside the mutex and
# confirming helgrind still fails it with these suppressions loaded.
#
# If your helgrind ever stops emitting these, nothing breaks: a suppression
# that matches nothing costs nothing.

{
   glibc-condvar-internal-refcount-Misc
   Helgrind:Misc
   ...
   fun:__pthread_cond_wait_common
   ...
}

{
   glibc-condvar-internal-refcount-Dubious
   Helgrind:Dubious
   ...
   fun:__pthread_cond_wait_common
   ...
}
